<div id="review_3067278762" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3067278762" />
    <a title="Settare (on hiatus)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13198822-settare-on-hiatus"><img alt="Settare (on hiatus)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590610257p2/13198822.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3067278762?book_show_action=true">Sep 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Settare (on hiatus)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Settare (on hiatus)" href="/user/show/13198822-settare-on-hiatus">Settare (on hiatus)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Anyone looking for some mental gymnastics</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Settare (on hiatus) by: </span>
      <a href="/user/show/86792478-shervin-pirani">Shervin pirani</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=reflections">reflections</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=politics-philosophy">politics-philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=bookclubs">bookclubs</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=american">american</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3067278762" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10107752709214003649">As the title suggests, this book is about Justice and explores moral dilemmas. Sandel introduces the main philosophical views about justice. He introduces key figures, advantages, and shortcomings of each view, and makes many examples for each of them. More than anything, this book (which is based on the author&apos;s popular Harvard course called <i>Justice</i>) is a compilation of exercises for Mental Gymnastics. You have to wrestle with your own beliefs, ideas, assumptions, and biases to navigate your wa</span>
  <span id="freeText10107752709214003649" style="display:none">As the title suggests, this book is about Justice and explores moral dilemmas. Sandel introduces the main philosophical views about justice. He introduces key figures, advantages, and shortcomings of each view, and makes many examples for each of them. More than anything, this book (which is based on the author's popular Harvard course called <i>Justice</i>) is a compilation of exercises for Mental Gymnastics. You have to wrestle with your own beliefs, ideas, assumptions, and biases to navigate your way through a complicated history of how humans have decided <i>"what's the right thing to do"</i>. <br />It's an interesting read. But of course, the topic is so complicated that there is no final, satisfying conclusion and the author is smart enough to know that. He introduces ideas, confuses you and challenges you, and leaves you with an open ending to take away what you will. <br /><br />For me personally, it was a very engaging and interesting read, but I am generally not a fan of occupying my mind with pointless philosophical questions for which there is never a correct answer. These sorts of books get repetitive and irrelevant after a while. I had fun thinking about endless moral dilemmas, but in the end, I can't say I "learned" something definitive and new from the book. I challenged my mind and moved on. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10107752709214003649" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


